---
import { Share05Icon } from "@hugeicons/core-free-icons";
import { HugeiconsIcon } from "@hugeicons/react";

import DefaultLayout from "@/layouts/DefaultLayout.astro";

const title = "New Maestro Studio";
const description =
  "Maestro Studio is the desktop app for mobile UI testing. Now completely redesigned, with contextual autocomplete.";
---

<DefaultLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <main>
    <article class="border-b">
      <div class="bordered-div-padding !pt-12 md:!pt-16 lg:!pt-20">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 md:space-y-10">
          <header class="space-y-4 md:space-y-5">
            <div class="space-y-2">
              <p class="section-overline">BLOG</p>
              <h1
                class="text-4xl leading-snug font-light tracking-tighter md:-translate-x-1 md:text-[2.625rem] lg:text-5xl"
              >
                New Maestro Studio
              </h1>
            </div>

            <div
              class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-x-2 gap-y-1 text-xs font-medium text-muted-foreground md:text-sm"
            >
              <span>Manu Armani</span>
              <span aria-hidden="true">•</span>
              <span>April 21, 2026</span>
            </div>
          </header>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bordered-div-padding !pt-0">
        <div class="article-content mx-auto max-w-3xl">
          <p>
            Today, we're announcing a completely redesigned Maestro Studio!
            Modern, elegant, and with new features that make building tests
            faster than ever.
          </p>

          <p>
            Maestro Studio is the desktop app for Maestro, the mobile UI testing
            framework used by teams at Microsoft, Meta, Uber, Amazon, DoorDash,
            and hundreds more. The idea behind it has always been simple:
            writing and maintaining UI tests for mobile apps shouldn't be
            painful. No complex setup, no steep learning curve, no brittle test
            maintenance.
          </p>

          <div class="my-10 overflow-hidden rounded-sm rounded-tl-lg border bg-muted/40">
            <iframe
              class="aspect-video h-auto w-full"
              src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/PZiaGqOo0xY?si=uR45OuqGpyU0RyCf"
              title="New Maestro Studio"
              frameborder="0"
              allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
              referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
              allowfullscreen></iframe>
          </div>

          <p>Here's what's new:</p>

          <h2>Autocomplete that knows your app</h2>

          <p>
            Maestro Studio now autocompletes commands, arguments, and selectors
            directly from your connected device.
          </p>

          <p>
            In practice this means: less time in the docs, fewer errors before
            you even run a test, and commands you didn't know existed showing up
            exactly when they're relevant. For new users, getting productive no
            longer requires memorizing Maestro's syntax. For experienced users,
            the repetitive parts of writing tests get significantly faster.
          </p>

          <p>
            If no device is connected, command and argument suggestions still
            work. Connect one, and selector suggestions instantly become
            dynamic.
          </p>

          <h2>Faster test creation via the emulator</h2>

          <p>
            Right-clicking on the emulator gives you immediate access to common
            commands and the correct selector in just a click. Building a test
            by navigating through your app is now the natural path - for
            developers and QA testers alike, including those coming from manual
            testing who want a modern tool without a long learning curve.
          </p>

          <p>Device connection is also significantly more robust in this release.</p>

          <h2>Upgrading</h2>

          <p>
            All your existing tests run as-is, with no migration needed. If
            you've only been using the CLI so far, now's a great time to try
            Studio. To get the latest version, update from within Studio or
            download it fresh:
          </p>

          <ul class="not-prose mt-8 list-disc space-y-3 pl-5">
            <li>
              <a
                class="thick-underline-link inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm font-medium text-foreground md:text-base"
                href="https://studio.maestro.dev/MaestroStudio.dmg"
              >
                Download for Mac
                <HugeiconsIcon icon={Share05Icon} className="size-4" strokeWidth={1.8} />
              </a>
            </li>
            <li>
              <a
                class="thick-underline-link inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm font-medium text-foreground md:text-base"
                href="https://studio.maestro.dev/MaestroStudio.exe"
              >
                Download for Windows
                <HugeiconsIcon icon={Share05Icon} className="size-4" strokeWidth={1.8} />
              </a>
            </li>
            <li>
              <a
                class="thick-underline-link inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm font-medium text-foreground md:text-base"
                href="https://studio.maestro.dev/MaestroStudio.AppImage"
              >
                Download for Linux
                <HugeiconsIcon icon={Share05Icon} className="size-4" strokeWidth={1.8} />
              </a>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
</DefaultLayout>

<style>
  .article-content {
    color: var(--color-foreground);
  }

  .article-content p {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .article-content p:first-child {
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }

  .article-content h2 {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    color: var(--color-foreground);
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 300;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
    line-height: 1.2;
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .article-content p {
      font-size: 1.0625rem;
    }

    .article-content h2 {
      font-size: 1.875rem;
    }
  }
</style>
